<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920218-0036</DOCNO><DOCID>920218-0036.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Ing. C. Olivetti andamp; C. S.p.A:   Labor Agreement Will Cut   Firm's Work Force by 1,500</HL><DATE>02/18/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   I.OLV LABOR</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)RESTRUCTURINGS, RECAPITALIZATION (RCN)</NS><RE>EUROPE (EU)ITALY (ITA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Italian computer maker Ing. C. Olivetti andamp; C. S.p.A. signeda labor accord with unions and government leaders to cut itswork force by 1,500 people.   The agreement fell far short of Olivetti's initial plans,announced last month, to cut its payroll by some 2,200.Olivetti has launched a companywide restructuring plan in aneffort to trim its costs and maintain competitiveness despitethe slump in the European computer market.</LP><TEXT>   Olivetti said last week that it expects to post aconsolidated 1991 loss of at least 290 billion lire ($237.8million), though the figure could be higher if extraordinarycharges linked to the restructuring plan are included.   The 1,500 workers will receive unemployment benefits,which are stipulated by law and paid for by the governmentand the company involved, until other jobs can be found forthem.   The government has made a commitment to employ 1,000 ofthe 1,500 workers that leave Olivetti. The other 500, ofwhich 320 workers will be from Northern Italy and 180 fromthe depressed Mezzogiorno region in the south, will beoffered early retirement incentives or alternative job offersin an attempt to phase them out.</TEXT></DOC>